From fcd2bf8f8259a62677121ddaace04b2b85817a68 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jake Teton-Landis <just.1.jake@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 5 Jul 2026 02:34:31 -0400
Subject: [PATCH 11/25] Versioned external-runtime handshake: v1 + capability
 bits, loud on skew
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The protocol handshake (cosignal spec §4.1 fact 7), both sides:

- react exports unstable_externalRuntimeProtocol: {version: 1,
  capabilities, providerProtocols} — the consumer side. Capability bits
  cover what this build implements (batch tokens, pass lifecycle,
  retirement, mutation window); bits for the planned capabilities
  (yield/resume, per-root commit, runInBatch, lineage, discardAllWip)
  are reserved so a stale fork build fails a consumer's handshake
  instead of silently missing events.
- The reconciler bakes in its own copy of the constants and echoes
  them as provider.protocol when it registers. Registration now
  REFUSES a react package that lacks the registry or speaks a
  different version (errors 602/603, extracted): version skew fails
  loudly at renderer load, never a silent no-op. The prior behavior
  (tolerate ReactSharedInternals.E === null by doing nothing) was
  exactly the silently-degraded mode the spec forbids.
- Suite grows to 10: handshake echo + both loud-failure paths.
- Also: replace the emit() for..of with Set#forEach (repo lint).

Precedent: gen-1 react-signals' unstable_reconcilerRuntime carried an
explicit version === 1 check.
